  "tables": [
    {
      "block_id": "2fe4750c-f3ba-80ce-886b-e2867ff83e65",
      "heading": "Abstract",
      "rows": [
        [
          "Context",
          "Teaching Method",
          "Recommender System Type",
          "Target of Recommendation",
          "Students",
          "Courses",
          "Data sources",
          "Initialization Method",
          "Updates to Recommendations",
          "Preprocessing Details",
          "Recommendation types",
          "Evaluation",
          "Comments",
          "Limitations"
        ],
        [
          "Higher Education",
          "Not Applicable",
          "Predictive Analytics (ML-based workload estimation)",
          "Course load predictions to inform course selection",
          "128 students for survey (596 ratings); 58,325 student-semester pairs for longitudinal analysis (9,106 students from Fall 2017 cohort)",
          "332 courses with ratings; ~10,000 courses in full catalog; 4,305 courses analyzed for discrepancy",
          "Survey data (ground truth: time load, mental effort, psychological stress ratings on 5-point Likert scales); Canvas LMS data (Spring 2017-2021); Enrollment records; course2vec embeddings",
          "Not applicable - supervised learning on surveyed course ratings. Models trained on 85% of 332 rated courses (5-fold CV); 15% held out for testing. Random search hyperparameter tuning (N=25 draws)",
          "Static model - trained once on Spring 2021 survey data, then scaled to historical enrollments. For courses missing LMS data in a semester, imputed via average predictions across semesters with available data (12.56% of offerings, avg 2.80 course iterations)",
          "LMS features (31 total): assignments (13; deadlines, count), submission comments (4; response rate, size), forum posts (14; reply speed, frequency). Enrollment features: credit hours, course GPA/SD, grade distributions, STEM status, prerequisites (total, satisfied in current/past semesters). course2vec: 300-dim embeddings + average prerequisite vectors. Missing LMS data: control variable imputation (keep 0s, add binary indicator) outperformed k-means. Averaged multiple ratings per course (1.80 avg) before training.",
          "Course-level workload predictions on continuous 5-point scale for: time load, mental effort, psychological stress, combined (average of 3). Scaled to predict semester load (PCL_sem) by summing course predictions per student per semester",
          "Cross-validation: MAE, % improvement over mean baseline. Test set: MAE with 95% CI via bootstrap (N=1,000). Longitudinal: compared PCL_sem vs credit hours across semesters, STEM vs non-STEM, transfer vs non-transfer. Stop-out & delayed graduation: logistic regression (AUC, McFadden's R², likelihood-ratio tests). Discrepancy analysis: partial correlations controlling for credit hours",
          "Ensemble model best for combined load: 21.9% improvement, MAE=0.626. Mental effort most predictive (18.2% improvement). Time load hardest (10% improvement). First semester highest by PCL_sem but lowest by credit hours. STEM courses show higher positive discrepancy (predicted > credit hours; M=0.54 vs -0.35 non-STEM). Students with low credit/high PCL_sem more likely to stop out (R²=0.39% vs 0.21% credit-only). Prerequisites most associated with discrepancy (r=0.54 for satisfied prereqs). High-discrepancy STEM courses (>2 SD) linked to stop-out. Average prerequisite course2vec explained more discrepancy variance (R²=0.75) than course's own vector (R²=0.63)",
          "No real-world deployment/intervention testing - can't confirm if CLA-informed decisions improve outcomes. Survey data from single semester (Spring 2021) at one institution (UC Berkeley). Simple semester load = sum of course predictions (no temporal granularity for assignment deadline overlaps). Models explain little variance in stop-out (AUC=0.57) and delayed graduation (AUC=0.55) directly. Credit hour adjustment suggestion (0.40 units) based on inference, not tested. Selection bias: AP credit holders may appear to have fewer satisfied prerequisites. Privacy constraints excluded assignment content analysis. Scale reliability moderate; needs more items for time load/stress subscales. Generalizability unknown across institutions/demographics"
        ]
      ],
      "index": 5
    }
  ],
